10 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ig-ru 3 sà-ri-dí iš-tù Ha-hi-im a-dí Ti-me-el-ki-a ||| Ten shekels of silver (were) for the wages for my three packers from Hahhum to Timelkiya
a-na ma-tim e-li-tim ||| near to the Upper Lands
GÍN AN.NA ||| shekel of tin
a-na Tu-ni-ia ÌR-di-ia qí-bí-ma um-ma La-ba-ar-na LUGAL GAL-ma ÌR-di at-ta ú-ṣur-an-ni ù a-na-ku ÌR-di <lu>ú-ṣur-ka URUTi4-ku-na-an URU-lim ù at-ta ÌR-di ù KUR-at-ka KUR-ti lu-ú-ṣur-ka KASKAL-ti-ia pí-te-et ù it-ti LÚ URUHa-hi-ia-ú lu-ú i-la-at ŠE.BA-šu ki-ma UR.GI7 a-ku-ul-šu GUD.HI.A ša ta-la-qè lu-ú ku-ú U8.UDU.HI.A ša ta-la-qè-ma lu-ú ku-ú-ma a-na mu-hi-šu lu-ú 2? i-la-at a-na-ku iš-tu an-na-nu-um ù at-ta iš-tu a-nu-um-ma-nu AN.BAR-zi-lu-ú ù UR.MAH ša iš-tu URUNi-ih-ri-ia ú-te-ru eš-me i-na-an-na šu-bi-lam ù ha-ši-ih-ta-ka ma-la ha-aš-ha-tam šu-up-ra-am-ma lu-ša-bi-la-kum lu-ú KÙ.BABBAR lu-ú ANŠE.KUR.RA ù ÌR-di húp-ti ÌR-di É-ti lu-ú-ša-bi-la-ak-kum i-nu-ma i-na URUZa-al-pa-ar a-la-kam-ma mBu-ul-li ÌR-di ù ÌR-ka šu-up-ra-aš-šu-nu-ti šum-ma qa-ni?-iKUŠ i-ba-aš-ši-ma šu-bi-lam ù za-ap-pí ANŠE.KUR.RA lu-ú pé-ṣú-ti lu-ú ṣa-al-mu-ti šu-bi-<la>-aš-šu-nu-ti ù a-wa-ti ša-ra-ti ša i-dá-bu-ub la ta-ša-mi qa-ni ri-mi ú-ṣur ù ši-bá-aṭ UR.MAH ú-ṣur ši-bá-aṭ še-la-bi-i la ta-aṣ-ba-at ša ša-ra-ti i-te-né-pu-uš ki-ma URUZa-al-pa-ar-ma e-pu-šu ù ša-tum qa-tam-ma e-pu-uš i-mi-tum ù <<ù>> šu-mé-lum a-wa-ti la te-eš-te-né-mi a-wa-ti-ia ú-ṣur ||| Speak to Tuniya, my servant. Thus the Labarna, the Great King. You are my servant. Protect me, and I will protect you, my servant. Tikunan is my city and you are my servant, and your land is my land, and I will protect you. My campaign is ready, and the man of Hahhum has prepared his forces. Devour his provisions like a dog. The oxen you take will be yours. The sheep you take will also be yours. There will be two assaults against him: I from here, and you from there. Now send me the iron and the lion, which I heard that they have returned from Nihriya, and then, whatever you wish for, as much as you want, write to me and I will send it to you – silver, horses, prisoners and local slaves I will send. When I arrive at Zalpar, send my servant Bulli and your servant to me. If there are qani at hand, then send that to me. Also, have them bring white or black horsehairs to me. Also, do not listen to the lies he utters, but keep to the bull's horns, protect the tail of the lion, and do not hold on to the tail of the fox – the one who constantly produces lies. What I did to Zalpar, I will do to him. Do not ever listen to words on the right or left. Heed my words.
a-na I-na-a qí-bi-ma ||| To Innaya
um-ma A-šùr-re-ṣí-ma ||| from Aššur-reṣi
a-ta-ma a-ma-kam lá wa-áš-ba-tí ||| You should not stay there
a-na Té-ga-r[a-ma] e-tí-iq-ma i-na Té-ga-ra-ma lu wa-áš-ba-tí ||| Go to Tegarama and stay in Tegarama
3 MA.NA 5 GÍN AN.NA a-na kà-ší-im áš-qú-ul ||| I paid three minas and five shekels of tin to the kaššum-official
1 1/2 MA.NA 5 GÍN AN.NA a-na ší-ip-ri-kà a-na Kà-ni-iški ||| 1 1/2 mina and five shekels of tin for your envoy to Kaneš
4 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR iš-tù Za-al-pá a-dí Kà-ni-iš ig-ri ANŠE áš-qúl ||| I paid four shekels of silver for the hire of a donkey from Zalpa to Kaneš
i-nu-mì a-na Za-al-pá e-tí-qú ||| When I went to Zalpa
ṭup-pu-a i-na Ha-qá i-ba-ší-ú a-ba-ú-a a-tù-nu KÙ.BABBAR ṣa-ru-pá-[am] li-iš-qú-lu-ma i-na ku-nu-ki-ku-nu ku-un-kà-ma šé-bi4-lá-nim šu-ma a-na Ha-qá a-li-ku-um DUMU um-mì-a-ni-im ša ki-sà-am i-ra-dí-ú lá-šu a-na Ší-ma-lá-ma a-na a-šar ša-lá-mì-im ep-ša ||| My tablets are in Haqa. Dear fathers, let them pay the silver, seal it with your seals, and have it sent here. If there is no affiliated trader in the possession of a 'purse' going to Haqa, then make it (travel) safely to Šimala instead.
3 GÚ [2]8 MA.NA a-wi-it Ì-lí-a-lim 10 MA.NA ša A-mur-A-šur 10 MA.NA ša I-dí-MAR.TU ŠU.NÍGIN 3 GÚ 48 MA.NA iš-tù A-limki a-dì A-pí-im 1 GÚ-tám 2 MA.NA 2 GÍN.TA ik-šu-dam 15 GÍN.TA qá-qá-da-tim 7 5/6 MA.NA 8 1/2 GÍN áš-qúl iš-tù A-[pí-im] a-dí ⌈Ha-qá⌉ 3 GÚ 40 [MA.NA] a-wi-sú 1 GÚ-tám 2 1/2 MA.NA 2 GÍN.TA ik-šu-dam 5 GÍN.TA qá-qá-da-tim 9 1/3 MA.NA 2 GÍN [áš]-qúl iš-tù Ha-qá a-dí Té-ga-ra-ma 3 GÚ 30 MA.NA a-wi-sú 1 GÚ-tám 1/2 MA.NA 4 GÍN.TA 1 5/6 MA.NA 9 GÍN áš-qúl 6 GÍN AN.NA ta-ší-a-tum i-ba-a-ba-at A-limki 5/6 MA.NA 5 GÍN i-na SA.TU ša Ha-qá 1/3 MA.NA 5 GÍN ša sà-e-tim 7 GÍN ša Pu-ra-tim 12 GÍN mu-ṭá-e ||| Three talents 28 minas (of tin) – the declared value of (the consignment belonging to) Ili-alum. Ten minas belonging to Amur-Aššur. Ten minas belonging to Iddin-Amurrum. In total three talents 48 minas. From the City to Apum 2 minas and 2 shekels per talent came on (as dātumšadduātum tax). Fifteen shekels was the headšadduātum tax. I paid 7 5/6 minas and 8 1/2 shekels. From Apum to Haqa its declared value was 3 talents and 40 minas. Two and a half minas and two shekels per talent came on (as dātumšadduātum tax). Five shekels each was the headšadduātum tax. I paid 9 1/3 minas and 2 shekels. From Haqa to Tegarama his shipment was three talents and 30 minas. At half a mina and 4 shekels per talent, I paid 1 5/6 mina and 6 shekels of tin. 6 shekels of tin was the transport cost for the outstanding claims in the City. 5/6 minas and 5 shekels in the mountains of Haqa. 1/3 mina and 5 shekels for sa'utum. 7 shekels for the Euphrates. 12 shekels were in deficit.
um-ma Puzur4-Ištar-ma a-na A-šur-ták-lá-ku-ma a-ma ša iš-tù Kà-ni-[iš] a-dí Za-al-pá ù Tí-me-[el-ki-a] a-gu5-ra-kà-ni ig-ri-[kà] ša-bu-a-tí ||| Puzur-Ištar said to Assur-taklaku: 'As for the fact that I hired you from Kaneš to Zalpa as well as Timelkiya – has your salary not been paid in full?'
i-na 21 ANŠE.[HI.A] ša i-na šé-pi-[a] ú-šé-li-a-ni ŠÀ.BA 1 ANŠE A-šur-ša-[ad]-ì-⌈lí⌉-e? a-na Tí-me-el-ki-a ir-de8-e 2 ANŠE.HI.A i-na Za-al-pá me-tù-ú 18 ANŠE.HI.A a-na Kà-ni-iš ú-šé-ri-ba-am ||| Out of the 21 donkeys that I brought up on my journey, thereof one was led to Timelkiya by Aššur-šad-ili, two donkeys died in Zalpa, and I made 18 donkeys enter Kaneš.
i-nu-mì a-na-ku i-na Tí-me-el-ki-a ú-ṣa-ni 15 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR a-na É wa-áb-ri a-dí-in a-na ṣé-ri-šu-nu a-na Za-al-pá a-li-ik-ma 5 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ag-mu-ur ||| When I myself left Timelkiya, I paid 15 shekels of silver for my inns. I went to them, to Zalpa, and I spent 5 shekels of silver.
šu-ma Za-al-pá-ma ta-lá-kà-nim É gu5-ba-áb-tim ṣú-ba-tí-ku-nu SIG5 ez-ba-ma šu-mì zu-uk-ra šu-ma a-na Tí-me-el-ki-a É A-dá-dá i-na Ša-lá-ah-šu-a ez-ba a-na mu-pá-zi-ri lá ta-dá-na ||| If you go (to) Zalpa itself, then leave your textiles of good quality in the house of the gubabtum and state my name. If (you head) to Timelkiya, then leave them in the house of Adada in Šalahšuwa. Do not hand them over to a smuggler.
81[+<gap> TÚG] ku-ta-nu iš-tí I-ku-pì-a DUMU Lu-lu 40 TÚG SIG5 DIRI na-sí-qá-ma i-Za-al-pá a-na Iš-me-Sú-en6 li-zi-z[u-ma] ší-tí TÚG.HI.[A] iš-tí-šu lu-šé-ri-ba-am 1 ANŠE le-zi-ib-šu-um ||| 81[+x] kutānukutānum textiles are owed by Ikun-piya, son of Lulu. Select 40 textiles of extra high quality, and let them remain for Išme-Su'en in Zalpa, while he should bring in the rest of the textiles with him. Leave him one donkey.
i-na ba-áb ha-ra-ni-šu i-na ša-pá-at na-ri-im i-na Za-al-pá ||| At his departure, at the bank of the river in Zalpa
iš-tù a-lim i-na e-lá-ni-a KÙ.BABBAR-áp-ki a-ša-qá-lá-ki-[im] ||| And on my way up from the City I will pay you the money
a-na ⌈be-lí⌉-ia qí-bí-ma um-ma Ia-si-im-su-mu-ú ÌR-ka-a-ma ||| To my Lord from Yasim-sumu, your servant
aš-šum e-te-eq mQa-qa-da-nim a-na Ha-aš-šiki a-na Ap-la-ha-an-da aq-bi ||| I spoke to Aplahanda (king of Carchemish) in regard to Qaqqadanum's journey to Haššum
mAb-du-⌈e⌉[ra-ah] iš-tu Za-al-baki il-[li-kam-ma] ||| Abdi-erah was coming here from Zalba
GIŠ.MÁ.GEŠTIN.NA lu-ma-li-kum-ma a-li-nik [i-d]i-im lu-ud-di-na-ak-kum ù a-l[i-i]k ||| I will fill your wine-boat, and I will also provide you with an escort, and then (you can) leave
a-li-ik i-d]i-šu LÚ Za-al-baki i-na Ka[r-ka-mi-nis]⌈ki⌉-ma wa-š[i-ib] ||| His escort, a man from Zalba, stays in Carchemish
a-li wa-áš-bu-ni qá-at-ku-nu li-iṣ-ba-sú-nu šu-ma a-Ma-a-ma Ṣí-lá-dIM lu-kà-ší-sú-<nu> lu a-Za-al-pá lu a-Te-ga-ra-ma lá i-bi-a-at lu-kà-ší-sú-nu ||| Wherever they are staying, your hand should seize them. If (they go) to Mamma, Ṣilla-Adad catch up with them. If (they go) to Zalpa or Tegarama, he should not tarry, but he should catch up with them.
i-na pá-ni-tim-ma áš-pu-ra-kum um-ma a-na-ku-ma šu-ma ILLAT-at-kà i-sà-ri-dam ù a-ta qá-dí-ma ILLAT-tí-kà sí-ir-dam-ma lu-qú-tám ša DAM.GÀR ša ta-ra-dí-ú TÚG.HI.A SIG5-tim bi-ir-ma i-na Ma-na-ma ú-lá i-na Ú-na-ap-sé-e-sí ší-tí TÚG.HI.A ma-ṭí-ú-tim lu i-na ša DAM.GÀR i-ba-ší-ú lu ša bé-ú-lá-tí-kà ù-lu i-na ša bé-ú-lá-at ṣú-ha-re-e i-ba-ší-ú qá-dí-ma tap-pá-e-kà a-na É.GAL-lim le-ru-bu-nim a-ni na-ab-ri-tum i-na Ur-šu i-ṣa-ba-at-ku-nu ki-ma ku-pá-um ma-du-ni a-na lu-qú-ut DAM.GÀR-ri-im ša ki-ma qá-qí-dí-a ú-lá áš-tap-ra-am ||| I wrote to you earlier, saying: 'If your caravan is being packed, then you too should pack together with your caravan, and choose textiles of good quality from the goods of the merchant that you are carrying, and in Mamma or in Unapsesi the rest of the less good textiles – both from what remains of the merchant's and from your own working capital and from the working capital of the servants – should enter the palace together with your partners.' Now the winter has caught up with you in Uršu. Since there is a lot of snow, I have not sent anyone in whom I could trust to get the goods of the merchant
a-ṣé-er E-ni-ša-ri-im a-dí AN.NA-ki-kà Ú-ṣú-ur-ší-Ištar áš-ta-pá-ar a-dí AN.NA-ki-kà ú Ú-ṣú-ur-ší-Ištar áš-ta-pá-ar iš-tù Za-al-pá i-tù-ru-nim-ma A-lá-ha-am a-ṭá-ra-dam ||| I have sent Uṣur-ša-Ištar to Enišarum concerning your tin. When they come back from Zalpa, I shall send Ali-ahum.
1/3 ma-na 5 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ší-im 10 GEMÉ-tim Áš-du i-na Ur-[šu a]-na Kà-nu-li aš-qúl-ma 1 GEMÉ-tám ší-a-ti i-na Za-al-pá a-na A-ma-ri-im DUMU Ib-ni-dIM a-dí-ší-ma a-na Kà-ni-ìški a-na ṣé-er A-šùr-ták-lá-ku DUMU A-lá-hi-im ir-de8-ší ||| 1/3 mina and 5 shekels of silver, the price of 10 slave-girls of Ašdu's, I paid to Kanuli in Uršu. I sold that one slave-girl to Amarum, son of Ibni-Adad, in Zalpa, and he led her to Aššur-taklaku, son of Ali-ahum, in Kaneš.
nam ni-da-na-ku-ma i-da-mì-iq-tim ta-ta-lá-ak a-dí TÚG.HI-tí ša a-na-kam té-zi-bu lá-ma-ma a-Ha-tù-uš e-li-a-ni TÚG.HI.A a-na URUDU ta-ad-nu ||| and I will complete the matter appropriately so that you go and provide textiles which you have left for me at Hattuš, textiles for copper<gap>
i-nu-mì a-na Za-al-pá ta-li-ku 10 MA.NA URUDU SIG5 a-na TÚG ša-a-mì-im a-dí-na-kum ší-im URUDU a-na am-tí-a dí-in ||| When you go to Zalpa, I will give you 10 minas of fine copper for that textile; the price of the copper will be determined by handshake
ki-ma dIM-ba-ni ù dUTU-ub-lam a-na Ha-na-ak-na-ak e-ru-bu-ni i-na É kà-ri-im iṣ-bu-tù-šu-nu ṭup-pá-am ša kà-ri-im ša ta-dí-nu-šu-nu-tí-ni e-ta-aṭ-ru-šu-nu ù a-ṣé-er pá-ni-im 8 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ša ú-ša-dí-ú-šu-nu-ni u4-ma-am 7 GÍN.TA KÙ.BABBAR ta-ah-sí-is-ta-áš-nu i-ta-ad-ú um-ma dIM-ba-ni ù dIM-ub-lá-ma <gap> i-tám ša-lá-ma lá a-na-kam nu-uš-té-bi4-il5 lá i-na ma-tí-ku-nu nu-uš-té-bi-il5 ki-ma ú-ma-sú-hu-šu-nu-ni a-na ma-tim e-ta-áb-tù a-na-kam eṭ-lu-tum ša ša-áp-tám il5-qí-ú-ni-ma ha-ra-nam kà-šu-da-am qá-bi4-ú-ni um-ma šu-nu-ma ha-ra-nam ni-lá-ak ki-ma dIM-ba-ni lá-šu-ú-ni É-a-ma-lik iš-tí-šu-nu ú-ṭá-hi-i um-ma a-na-ku-ma a-sú-ri a-na ma-at Za-al-pá e i-li-ku-ú a-ma-kam e-kà i-ṣé-ri-šu-nu li-li-ik a-na Kà-ni-iš ha-ra-nam qá-bi4-ú a-sú-ri a-na ma-at Za-al-pá e i-li-ku-ú ||| When Adad-bani and Šamaš-ublam entered Hanaknak, they seized them in the Office of the Colony. They confiscated the tablet from the Colony, which you gave to them, and on top of the 8 shekels of silver that they made them deposit, they have today drawn up their memoranda (acknowledging a debt) for 7 shekels per person. Adad-bani and Adad-ublam together said as follows: 'Ask the <gap> that we have not traded here – we have not traded in your country'. Because they maltreated them, they fled into the countryside. Here, the men who took the wool and promised to catch up with a caravan said: 'We will go on the journey'. But given that Adad-bani was not present, I confronted Ea-malik together with them, and I said: 'No matter what, they are not to go to the Land of Zalpa'. You should keep an eye on them there. They have promised me a trip to Kaneš. They are under no circumstances to go to the Land of Zalpa.
a-na É wa-áb-ri-a ||| for an inn
a-na É.GAL-lim ||| to the palace
ú-nu-t[ám] i-na Té-ga-ra-ma e-zi-ib-ma a-na-ku a-na Ha-tim a-ta-lá-a[k] ší-ma-am ša Ha-tim a-na-ku na-áš-a-ku ||| I left the goods in Tegarama and personally I went to Hattum. I myself carry the proceeds from Hattum.
a-hu-a a-tù-nu šu-ma a-ma-kam ta-le-e-a am-tám! ú ṣú-úh-ra-am ma-lá ta-le-e-a-ni šu-ul!-ha-ni-im a-dí KÙ.BABBAR 10 GÍN gu5-um-ra-ma a-na Té-ga-ra-ma ú Ha-tim šé-bi-lá-ni-ší šu-ma ma-ṣa-ra-tum da-na-ma a-na ú-ṣa-im lá na-ṭú ú-ṭa-tim ša ša-na-at šu-up-kà-ší-im ṣú-ha-ru a-na Lu-hu-za-tí-a li-ik-šu-du-ni ||| Dear brothers, if it is possible for you there, dispatch the slave-girl and the children, as you are able. Make an arrangement of some 10 shekels of silver and have her brought to Tegarama or Hattum. If the guard posts are strong, and it is not feasible to set out, then measure out grain to (supply) her for one year. The servants should reach me in Luhuzattiya.
i-na Té-ga-ra-ma wa-áš-⌈ba⌉-ku <gap> i-na dUTU-ši ṭup-pí ta-ša-me-a-ni A-lá-hu-um lu a-na Hu-ra-ma lu a-na Ku-ša-ra a-na ṣé-ri-a li-li-kam ||| I am staying in Tegarama <gap> On the day you hear my letter, Ali-ahum should come and meet me in either Hurama or in Kuššara.
2 1/2 MA.NA ni-ga-li i-na Té-ga-ra-ma a-na É ub-ri a-dí-in 1/3 MA.NA ni-ga-li a-na ki-ri-[i]m i-na Ta-[a]l-pá 15 GÍN a-šar ÌR i-mu-tù a-É ub-ri 1/3 GÍN 7 1/2 ŠE a-na ki-ri-im i-Sú-pá-na 1/2 GÍN a-na ša ma-ṣa-ra-tim ||| I paid 2 1/2 mina in sickles for an inn in Tegarama. 1/3 mina of sickles for wine in Talpa. I paid 15 shekels for an inn at the place where the servant died. 1/3 and 7 1/2 grains for wine in Supana. Half a shekel for the guards.
a-na 10-tim! ša Té-ga-ra-ma um-ma A-ni-šu-ki-ba-ma ba-ru-lu-um ša Tí-pu-ur-zi-a-ma a-ba-ú-a a-hu-a a-tù-nu ||| To the ten-man board of Tegarama from Anišu-kiba, the barullum-official in Tiburziya: Dear fathers and brothers
i-na me-at 45 TÚG.HI.A qá-dì ša kà-ṣa-ri ša šé-ep A-mur-Ištar ŠÀ.BA 3 TÚG [š]a A-ki-dì-e i-na Ha-hi-im DUMU e-mì-kà ⌈e⌉-zi-ib ||| he should leave 45 pieces of garment<gap>
pá-zu-ur-tù-šu DUMU Èr-ra-a a-ṣé-er Pu-šu-ke-en6 ú-šé-ri-na-ma pá-zu-ur-tù-šu i-ṣí-bi-it-ma Pu-šu-ke-en6 É.GAL-lúm iṣ-ba-at-ma a-na ki-šé-er-ší-im i-dì ma-ṣa-ra-tum da-na a-na Lu-hu-za-ti-a Hu-ra-ma Ša-lá-ah-šu-a a-na ma-ti-ša a-dì ša pá-zu-ur-tim ru-ba-tum ta-áš-pur ||| his agent was caught smuggling and Pušu-ken was jailed; a garrison was sent to Luhuzattiya, Hurama and Šalahšuwa in their lands, as the queen had instructed
