DUMU ší-ip-ri-a a-ṣé-ri-kà li-ta-lá-kam ||| my messenger should depart to you
KÙ.BABBAR áb-na-tim ik-nu-uk-ma ||| I sealed the silver
i-na 10 na-ru-uq ú 2 DÚG ŠE-im ar-ša-tí ša Pì-lá-ah-Ištar e-zi-ba-ni ||| Out of 10 sacks and 2 pots of barley that Pilah-Ištar left
4 DUG a-na ⌈X⌉-i-ša-ma ú-šé-bi4-il5 ||| 4 pots to Taišama I brought
KÙ.BABBAR šu-a-tí a-ru-ba-im Ma-ma-im ú-šé-bi-lu-šu ||| quoted in Balkan 1957: 32
ša-pì-ri-im ma-ma-i-im ||| šāpirum of Mamma
na-ri-ib-tám a-ra-ak-tám da-mì-iq-tám ú-ta-ar-tám ||| soft, long and extremely good
a-na ru-ba-im iš-tù sí-kà-tim i-tù-a-ri-šu i-ba-tí-šu am-hu-ur-šu-ma ||| Upon the king's return from the sikkātum, I confronted him in his territory
ki-ma ší-lá-tám lá i-šu-ú É.GAL-lúm ra-dí-šu a-na ba-té iš-pu-ra-ma a-na Wa-ah-šu-ša-na a-tù-ar ||| Since he did nothing wrong, the palace wrote to its guide at the frontier and I will return to Wahšušana
um-ma I-ku-pí-a <gap> a-na En-nam-A-šùr qí-bí-[ma] ||| From Ikun-piya and <gap> to Ennam-Assur:
50 TÚG.HI ku-ta-ni ||| 50 kutānukutānum textiles
25 ma-na AN.NA ||| 25 minas of tin
1/3 ma-na 2/3 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ||| 1/3 mina 2/3 shekel of silver
25 ku-ta-nu 13 ma-na.TA ta-ad-nu ||| 25 kutānus were sold at 13 minas each
25 ku-ta-nu 12 ma-na.TA ta-ad-nu ||| 25 kutānus were sold at 12 minas each
18 ma-na AN.NA 10 ma-na.TA ||| 18 minas of tin were sold at 10 minas each
ší-tí AN.NA-ki-kà 3 ma-na 15 GÍN ||| The rest of your tin: 3 minas 15 shekels
55 ma-na ší-im ANŠE.HI-kà ||| 55 minas was the price of your donkeys
31 ma-na ší-im KÙ.BABBAR ša li-bi4 Dan-A-šùr ||| 31 minas the price of the silver in Dan-Aššur's possession
15 GÚ 24 2/3 ma-na URUDU ma-sí-um ||| the total of your copper: 15 talents 24 2/3 minas of washed copper
18 ma-na SIG5 ša-du-a-at URUDU-i-kà ù ANŠE.HI-kà ni-iš-qúl ||| We paid 18 minas of good copper as the transport tariff on your copper and your donkeys
41 TÚG.HI.A-tí-kà a-na Hu-ra-ma ú-šé-tí-qám-ma ha-ra-an sú-qí-ni ar-dí-a-ma šál-ma-ku i-Ku-bu-ur-na-at wa-áš-ba-ku ni-is-ha-tim a-dan-ma a-ma-lá té-er-tí-kà lu-qú-ut-kà a-na Dur4-hu-mì-it a-ra-de8 ||| I made your (remaining) 41 textiles go to Hurama, I led them (onto) the Narrow Track, and now I (have arrived) safely. I am staying in Kuburnat. I will now pay the nishātušadduātum tax, and in accordance with your message, I will lead your goods to Durhumit.
AN.NA a-na e-ba-a[r] Ša-la-ah-šu-wa lá ú-šé-tù-qú ki-ma ša-lá-am AN.NA-ki e-ba-ar Tí-me-el-ki-a-ma AN.NA a-na Dur4-hu-mì-it lu-šé-tí-qú šu-ma ⌈ša?⌉ Ku-bu-ur-na-at a-ma-kam wa-áš-bu AN.NA li-⌈ší-ib⌉-ma ||| Do not let them send the tin via Šalahšuwa. For the safety of my tin, they should let the tin travel via Timelkiya to Durhumit. If people from Kuburnat are staying there, then leave the tin to them, and <gap>
iš-tù Tí-me-el-ki-a ha-ra-an sú-qí-ni-ma a-šar ša-lam5 lu-qú-tí-a er-ba <gap> šu-ma i-na Ku-bu-ur-[na-at] Ha-na-ak-na-ak ú-lá Dur4-hu-mì-it TÚG-tí SIG5 a-ší-mì-im e-ri-šu-ku-nu 1/2 MA.NA.TA KÙ.BABBAR a-na i-ta-aṭ-lim dí-na lá tù-ša-ra ||| <gap> enter the Narrow Track from Timelkiya for the safety of my merchandise <gap> If they demand good textiles from you for sale, be it Kuburnat, in Hanaknak, or in Durhumit, then you should sell the good textiles for cash on delivery for at least half a mina a piece.
ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim-ma a-na Du-ur-hu-mì-it ú-là Tí-iš-mu-ur-na a-li ||| on the narrow track, and either to Durhumit or to Tišmurna
iš-tù Ku-bu-ur-na-at a-dí Dur4-hu-mì-it ni-tù-ru-ni ||| we returned from Kuburnat to Durhumit
a-na Dur4-hu-mì-it a-šu-mì-ki e-tí-iq-ma ||| I shall go to Durhumit for your sake
1 1/2 GÍN AN.NA i-na a-al Bu-uṭ-[n]a-tim a-É wa-áb-ri a-dí-in ||| I paid 1 1/2 shekels of tin for lodgings in āl Buṭnātim
3 GÍN AN.NA i-na Ha-ni-kà wa-ṣa-i-ni a-na É ub-ri a-dí-in ||| I paid 3 shekels of tin for lodgings at our departure from Hanika
6 GÍN AN.NA a-na ni-is-ha-tim ša TÚG.HI.A i-na Ha-na-ak-na-ak a-dí-in ||| I paid 6 shekels of tin (a piece) as import tax on the textiles in Hanaknak
14 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ší-im áš-qúl ||| 14 shekels of silver was the price I paid
3 GÍN AN.NA iš-tù Ha-na-ak-na-ak i-<wa>-ṣa-i-a a-na É ub-ri-ni a-dí hu-lu-qá-e ni-iš-e-ú a-dí-in ||| I paid 3 shekels of tin at our departure from Hanaknak while we searched for the things that had been lost
1 1/2 GÍN AN.NA i-na Ta-pá-kà-áš a-kà-ší-im a-dí-in ||| I paid 1 1/2 shekels of tin to the official in Tapaggaš
1/2 MA.NA URUDU a-né-bar-tim i-ša Dur4-hu-mì-it a-dí-in ||| I paid 1/2 mina of copper at the ford in the territory of Durhumit
3 ma-na URUDU SIG5 ni-is-ha-tim i-na Dur4-hu-mì-it a-kà-ší-im a-dí-in ||| I paid 3 minas of refined copper to the official as import tax in Durhumit
10 ma-na URUDU ší-kam lu a-É ub-ri lu gám-ri i-na Wa-ah-šu-ša-na ||| 10 minas of šikku-copper for lodgings and expenses in Wahšušana
a-na-kam Šu-Ku-bu-u[m] ha-ra-šu-ma a-na Ku-bu-ur-na-at ú-ša-hi-sú-ma um-ma a-na-ku-ma a-dí Ha-na-ak-na-<ak> šé-pì-kà dí-in ||| Here Šu-Kubum was instructed to go to Kuburnat, but I said: 'Set your feet to Hanaknak'
šu-ma a-na Wa-ah-šu-ša-na [ha-ra-num lá pá]-tí-a-at [lu a]-⌈Ha⌉-na-ak-na-ak lu a-Ku-bu-ur-na-at a-šar ha-ra-nu-um pá-tí-a-at-ni lu-qú-tí šé-bi-lam ||| If the road to Wahšušana is not open, have my goods brought here to Hanaknak or to Kuburnat where the road is open
ša-áp-tám Puzur4-A-šur a-na ma-at Ta-ah-ru-wa ú-šé-ra-áb-ma iš-tù ma-at Ta-ah-ru-wa ú-ṣí-a-ma 2 2/3 MA.NA KÙ.BABBAR ša ki-ma I-dí-Sú-in i-na Ku-bur-na-at i-ša-qal ||| Puzur-Aššur will take the wool go into the Land of Tahruwa, he will leave the Land of Tahuruwa, and he will pay the 2 2/3 minas of silver to the representatives of Iddin-Su'en in Kuburnat
a-na Ku-bu-ur-na-at [e-ru-u]b-ma Kà-sú-a [ú-lá] ak-šu-ud i-na ma-at [Ta-ah]-ru-a wa-ša-áb [la-at-bi4]-a-ma iš-tù ma-at [Ta-ah-ru]-a a-na Hu-ra-ma [<gap>]-ar?-dí a-na Ku-bu-ur-na-at [šu-up-r]a-am ||| I went into Kuburnat, but I did not catch up with Kazua. He is staying in the Land of [Tahu]ruwa. Let me set out and come [<gap>] from the Land of [Tahuruw]a to Hurama. [Write] to Kuburnat <gap>
21 GÚ ša-áp-tám ša Kà-né-eš ša É.GAL-lim En-um-A-⌈šùr⌉ DUMU Šál-ma-A-šur a-na Ì-[lí-dan] i-na Ku-bur-na-at i-š[a-qal-ma] ṣú-ha-ru ša En-um-A-šùr Ša-lim-ar-dí 21 GÚ SÍG.HI.A i-na Ku-bur-na-at ú-sà-na-aq-šu-ma ANŠE.HI.A ša En-nam-A-šur SÍG.HI.A a-na Tù-ku-ub-tù ú-šé-ru ||| Ennum-Aššur son of Šalim-Aššur shall give 21 talents of wool from Kaneš, from the palace, to Ili-dan in Kuburnat, and Ennam-Aššur's servant, Šalim-wardi, will check the 21 talents of wool in Kuburnat, and they shall release the wool to Tukuptu on Ennam-Aššur's donkeys
a-na Ì-[lí-dan i-na Ku-bur-na-at ||| to Ili-dan in Kuburnat
me-eh-ra-at ṭup-pé-e ha-ru-mu-tim ša Ku-bu-ur-na-at ||| Copies of certified tablets from Kuburnat
Bu-ṣí-a ša Ku-bu-ur-na-at ||| Buṣiya of Kuburnat
8 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR mu-sú-kà-e ša-du-a-tám i-Ku-bu-ur-na-at i-dí-ma ||| He paid 8 shekels of impure silver in šaddu'utumšadduātum tax in Kuburnat
1½ ma-[na URUDU] Ku-na-na-ma-i-u[m] ||| 1 1/2 minas of copper from Kunanamit
um-ma šu-nu-ma ha-ra-nam ni-lá-ak ||| We will go on the journey
um-ma a-na-ku-ma a-sú-ri a-na ma-at Za-al-pá e i-li-ku-ú ||| No matter what, they are not to go to the Land of Zalpa
te-er-ta-ku-nu a-na Ha-na-ak-na-<ak> li-li-kam-ma ||| send their message to him in Hanaknak
um-ma E-a-ma-lik-ma 1/2 MA.NA 6 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR iš-tù li-mì-im Da-dí-a DUMU Šu-lá-áp-ra-at tù-kà-al i-na A-ku-wa aṣ-ba-at-kà-ma um-ma a-ta-ma a-na Ha-tù-uš e-li-ma ṭup-pa-am ša ší-be-kà kà-li-ma-ni a-na Ha-tù-uš e-li-a-ma ša ki-ma ku-a-tí a-wa-tám lá i-ta-ad-nu-ni a-na ša ki-ma i-a-tí qí-bi-ma a-ma-kam ki-a-am šu-ma KÙ.BABBAR ša-qá-lam lá i-mu-a ša-am-ri-ṣa-ku a-na Ha-na-ak-na-ak té-er-ta-ku-nu li-li-kà-ma ||| You have borrowed half a mina and 6 shekels of silver from the (year of) the eponym Dadiya son of Šu-Ilabrat. I seized you in Amkuwa, where you said: 'Go up to Hattuš and produce a (debt) note with your witness for me'. So I went up to Hattuš, but your representatives did not give me their word. Tell my representatives: 'If he refuses to pay the money there, it will make me angry'. Let your message reach me in Hanaknak.
1 GÚ a-lá-ni SIG5 ša Ha-na-ak-na-ak ||| 1 jar of good quality acorns from Hanaknak
ha-r[a]-an sú-qí-nim-ma ||| on the Narrow Track
a-na Du-ur-hu-mì-it ú-là Tí-iš-mu-ur-na ||| to either Durhumit or to Tišmurna
i-na Tí-iš-mur-na URUDU a-na kà-ú-nim lá-šu ||| It is impossible to convert any copper in Tišmurna
URUDU a-na Dur4-hu-mì-it lu-šé-ri-ba-ma a-na SIG5 lu nu-ta-er ||| let me bring the copper into Durhumit and we can exchange it to (copper of) good quality there
10 GÚ URUDU SIG5 ší-im 50 TÚG.HI.A i-na Tí-ša-mu-ur-na am-hu-ur ||| I received 10 talents of fine copper as the proceeds of 50 textiles in Tišmurna
ší-im AN.NA I-dí-A-šùr nu-ša-áš-a-ma ||| We will make Iddin-Aššur buy (more) for the proceeds from the tin
lu ší-im TÚG.HI.A ú AN.NA lá-mu-num i-ba-ší ||| There is poor (copper) available for the textiles and the tin
i-na ma-at Hi-ru-ùh nu-kà-an-ma iš-té-ni-iš 30 GÚ nu-ma-lá-ma nu-ša-babar-ma Ta-az-ku-ul iš-tí ša bi4-lá-tim a-na Wa-ah-šu-ša-na ni-ṭá-ra-ad ||| we will convert (the copper) in the Land of Hiruh, and we will top it up to a total of 30 minas and break it up (for transport), and then we will send Tazkul (with it) to Wahšušana with the porters
2 [a]-nu-qú š[a a-mu-tim] ša A-šur-i-mì-tí i-na Du[r4]-hu-mì-i[t] ta-dí-nam ||| You gave me 2 rings of [amūtum] belonging to Aššur-imitti in Durhumit
i-na É.GAL-lim ga? e? pu ar a-na 4 GÚ 5[0] MA.NA URUDU a-dí-ší ||| I sold them for 4 talents 50 minas copper in the palace
I have paid 8 1/2 mina of refined copper as šadu'utum-tax in Durhumit. I deposited 14 mina of bad copper in Zimišhuna. Two minas: Buitak of Tišmurna ||| I have paid 8 1/2 mina of refined copper as šadu'utumšadduātum tax in Durhumit. I deposited 14 mina of bad copper in Zimišhuna. Two minas: Buitak of Tišmurna
8 1/2 MA.NA URUDU SIG5 ša-du-a-tám i-na Du-ur-hu-mì-it a-dí-i 14 ma-na URUDU lá-mu-n[am] i-Zi-mì-is-hu-n[a] a-dí-i 2 ma-na Bu-i-ta-a[k?] ša Tí-iš-mu-ur-na 2 ma-na wa-ṣí-tum 15 GÍN.TA i-ANŠE.HI.A a-na kà-ší-im a-dí-in i-Wa-ah-šu-ša-na 1 MA.NA.TA da-tum a-di Pu-ru-uš-ha-dim ik-šu-ud ||| 8 1/2 minas of good copper from Durhimit, up to 14 minas of copper as deduction in Zimishuna, up to 2 minas to Buitak of Tišmurna. 2 minas was the exitšadduātum tax. 15 shekels per donkey I paid to the kaššum-official in Wahšušana. 1 mina per (animal) came on as fees until Purušhaddum.
ki-ma ANŠE.HI-a iš-tù Wu-lá-ma ur-du-ni-ni ú-ma-kál lá tù-uš-bi4-tá-šu-nu a-ṣé-er Am-ri-a a-Tí-iš-mur-na ṭù-ur-da-šu-nu ||| When my donkeys come down to you from Wulama, you are not to let them remain a single day. Send them straight on to Amriya in Tišmurna
1 1/4 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR a-šu-mì Ha-ha-ma a-na ma-ar-ší i-na Ší-na-hu-tí áš-qú-ul ||| I paid 1 1/4 shekels for leather straps on behalf of Hahha in Šinahuttum
1 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ší-im du-dí-na-tí ša ZABAR i-na Ha-tù-uš a-dí-šu ||| I paid him 1 shekel of silver – the price of a bronze pectoral – in Hattuš
3 MA.NA URUDU ni-is-ha-tí-šu a-šu-mì E-nam-A-šùr i-na Ší-na-hu-tí áš-qú-ul ||| His nishātum was 3 minas of copper, which I paid on behalf of Ennam-Aššur in Šinahuttum
ANŠE.HI.A li-zi-zu-ma lu-ša-ki-il-šu-nu ||| Let the donkeys be, and let me feed them.
1/2 ma-na 2 GÍN URUDU a-na ub-ri-ni áš-qúl ||| I paid 32 shekels of copper for our lodgings
ša i-nu-me SÍG-tám iš-tù Ší-na-hu-tim a-na Dur4-hu-mì-it ni-iz-bi-lu-ni ||| As for the time when we transported the wool from Šinahuttum to Durhumit
ANŠE ša En-nam-We-er a-ší-ni-šu SÍG-tám a-na Dur4-hu-mì-it En-nam-We-er is-ri-sú ||| Ennam-Wer twice packed the donkey belonging to Ennam-Wer with wool to Durhumit.
dU pihami ša URUSanahwitta ||| The Stormgod of Sanahwitta
ší-ma-am ša KÙ.BABBAR 10 GÍN e-li-a-ni ša-ma-ma šé-bi-lam i-na Ha-tù-uš ú Ta-am-ni-a uš-té-ba-al ||| Make a purchase that will produce at least 10 shekels of silver and send it here. I will do business in Hattuš or Tawiniya.
a-dí URUDU ša A-mur-Ištar a-na ša ki i-a-tí URUDU i-na Pu-ru-uš-ha-tim ta-da-nam ú-lá i-mu-ú ha-ra-ni a-na Pu-ru-uš-ha-tim ||| In regard to the copper belonging to Amur-Ištar, they refused to hand over the copper to my representatives in Purušhaddum, so my journey goes to Purušhaddum
šu-ma TÚG.HI-tù-a ša Za-al-pá ù ša Hu-ra-ma e-ru-bu-nim ha-ra-an Ta-wi-ni-a-ma a-na Wa-ah-šu-ša-na áb-kà-šu-nu a-na-kam É.GAL-lam ni-iš-al-ma um-ma šu-ut-ma Kà-ni-ší-ú lu-úṣ-ú-ma ú a-tù-nu a-tal-kà ||| If the textiles (coming) from Zalpa and those from Hurama enter (Kaneš), then send them by the Tawiniya road to Wahšušana. Here, we have asked the palace, and they say: '(When) the Kanešites leave, you too come here'.
um-ma kà-ru-um Kà-ni-iš-ma a-na ša-qí-il5 da-tim Ku-li-a ší-ip-ri-ni kà-ri-im Dur4-hu-mì-it Ha-tù-uš Ta-am-ni-a Tù-ùh-pí-a a-dí Ni-na-ša-a ||| From the Kaneš Colony to the dātum-payers, Kuliya our messenger, and the colonies in Durhumit, Hattuš, Tamniya, Tuhpiya until Ninašša.
1 2/3 GÍN ša da-at 5 ni-a-tí 1/3 GÍN a-na NINDA i-na Ta-wi-ni-a 2 MA.NA URUDU i-na ba-té ša Tí-iš-mur-na ik-lu-ú-ni-ma a-dí-in ||| 1 2/3 shekels for the fees for five of us. A third of a shekel was for bread in Tawiniya. They held me back and I paid 2 minas of copper in the territory of Tišmurna.
a-na kà-ri-im Kà-ni-iš qí-bi-ma um-ma kà-ru-um Ta-am-ni-a-ma ší-ip-ru-ú ša kà-ri-im Dur4-hu-mì-it a-na ru-ba-im ša Ta-am-ni-a a-na ta-mu-im er-ba-am ub-lu-ni-šu-ma um-ma šu-ut-ma a-na ší-ip-ri-ma a-li ší-ip-ru ša a-ba-e-a ša kà-ri-im Kà-ni-iš šu-nu li-li-ku-nim-ma iš-tí-šu-nu ma-mì-tám a-lá-qé-ma ú-ma-sà-ah-ni-a-tí-ma um-ma šu-ut-ma a-la-am e-pá-áš ú a tí er-ba-am ni-ší-šu-um ú-za-ku-nu ni-ip-té a-li-kam e ú-ma-sí-hu ||| To the Kaneš Colony from the Tamniya Colony. The envoys from the Durhumit Colony went in (before) the king of Tamniya, bringing him a gift (in order) to (make him) swear (an agreement), but he said as follows to the envoys: 'Where are the envoys of my fathers, of the Kaneš Colony? They should come here, and then I will acccept a sworn agreement with them'. He is treating us with contempt, saying: 'I will build a city, and I [ <gap> long break <gap>] we brought him a gift. We have (hereby) informed you. They should not treat a messenger with contempt.
um-ma A-šur-i-mì-tí a-na Hu-ra-ṣa-nim qí-bi-ma ||| Thus says Aššur-imitti to Huraṣanu
a-pu-tum i-na u4-mì-im ša a-na Ta-a-ni-a té-ru-bu té-eb-a-ma a-tal-kam ||| On the day you enter Ta-a-ni-a, please take off and come to me
lu-la-am 2 ma-na ù 3 ma-na a-na 10 u4-me ra-ku-sà-ku ||| I am (contractually) bound for 2-3 minas of lulā'um within 10 days
šu-ma a-dí A-li-a-ša kà-ša-dí-kà 10 u4-me im-ta-la i-na A-li-a-ša-ma ú-nu-ut-kà e-zi-ib-ma té-eb-a-ma a-tal-kam ||| If you can reach Aliašša within the 10 days, then leave your goods in Aliašša and take off and come to me
GÍR ša Aššur ||| dagger of Aššur
3 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR a-É ub-ri i-na Pu-ru-uš-ha-dim a-dí-in ||| I paid 3 shekels of silver for my lodgings in Purušhaddum
1 1/2 MA.NA URUDU iš-tù Pu-ru-uš-ha-dim a-dí Ša-lá-tù-a-ar ik-šu-dí ||| 1 1/2 minas of copper from Purušhaddum to Šalatuwar
10 MA.NA URUDU a-dí i-Ša-lá-tù-a-ar úṣ-a-ni ga-me-er ||| Until I left Šalatuwar, 10 minas of copper were spent
1 1/2 MA.NA URUDU a-dí Tuhx-(TUR4)-pì-a ik-šu-dí ||| (The expenses) amounted to 1 1/2 minas of copper until Tuhpiya
3 MA.NA URUDU a-dí Dur4-hu-mì-it ik-šu-dí ||| (The expenses) amounted to 3 minas of copper until Durhumit
dIM-ba-ni iš-tù Ša-lá-tù-wa-ar i-pá-ni I-ku-pí-a a-mì-ša-am i-tal-kam ||| Adad-bani left Šalatuwar to (go to) Ikun-piya
i-na Tù-ùh-pí-aki im-hu-ru-šu ||| they had met him in Tuhpiya
um-ma kà-ru-um Kà-ni-iš-ma a-na kà-ar kà-ar-ma ú wa-bar-ra-tim a-dí Tù-ùh-pí-a qí-bi-ma ||| From the Kaneš Colony to every single Colony and Station until Tuhpiya
um-ma kà-ru-um Kà-ni-iš-ma a-na kà-ar kà-ar-ma ú wa-b[a]-ra-tim ú En-na-Sú-in ší-ip-ri-ni a-dí Tù-ùh-pì-a qí-bi4-ma ||| From the Kaneš Colony to all Colonies and Stations, and our envoy, Ennam-Su'en, until Tuhpiya
ki-ma AN.NA a-na Tù-ùh-pì-a iš-li-mu té-er-ták-nu li-l[i-kam] ||| When the tin reaches Tuhpiya safely, then let your message come here
É A-am-ku-a-i-tim ||| house of the queen of Amkuwa
a-ha-at ru-ba-im Ša-ša-sá-ma-i-im ||| sister of the king of (Ša)šasama
tí-ra-at e-kál-lim ||| offices of the palace
be-el a-limki ||| town prefect
be-el ha-ṭí-tim ||| staff holder
2 1/3 ma-na ga-ma-ar-kà ša Pu-ru-uš-ha-dim ú-la iš-ku-nu ||| They have not (yet) settled the 2 1/3 minas – your expense for Purušhaddum
2 GÚ 15 MA.NA URUDU i-na Wa-ah-šu-ša-na IGI I-a-tal-kà um-mì-kà a-dí-na-kum 1 TÚG a-na Ha-nu ša Wa-aš-ha-ni-a a-na 40 MA.NA URUDU a-dí-in-ma ||| I sold 2 talents 15 minas of copper in your mother Yatalka's presence in Wahšušana. I likewise sold one textile to Hanu in Wašhaniya for 40 minas of copper
a-dí URUDU ta-áš-pu-ra-am um-ma a-ta-ma 20 GÚ URUDU i-sí-ki-im Ni-na-ša-i-um a-dí Wa-áš-ha-ni-a li-pu-ša-am ||| As for the copper, you wrote and said: 'Let the man of Ninašša convey 20 minas of copper in a sikkum-transport as far as Wašhaniya
i-na Ni-na-ša-a 15 MA.NA URUDU ag-mu-ur 10 MA.NA [a]-na ag-ri-im [ša] iš-tí-a is-hu-ru [áš-q]ul i-na Wa-áš-ha-ni-a a-dí-šu-um 5 ma-na URUDU il5-qé iš-tù Ni-na-ša-a ú-ṣí-ma i-na At-hu-ru-uš-na 5 ma-na URUDU i-ṣé-ri-a il5-qé-ú ||| In Ninašša I paid 15 minas of copper. I paid 10 minas for the hireling who was delayed with me. I gave them to him in Wašhaniya. He took 5 minas of copper. He left Ninašša, and in Athurušna they took 5 minas of copper on my account.
[a]-šar ha-ra-an Ma-li-ta-ma a-[n]a [Wa]-ah-šu-ša-na i-ta-á[p-té-ú] ||| At the place where the Malitta road to Wahšušana opens
1/3 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ||| 1/3 shekel of silver
10 GÍN AN.NA ||| 10 shekels of tin
ru-ba-um Wa-áš-ha-na-i-um i-li-kam ||| The king of Wašhaniya came here
a-na Pu-ru-uš-ha-dim ù Ha-tim ik-ta-lá-ni ||| He has kept me from going to Purušhaddum or Hattum
a-dí-i 5 u4-me-e ú-ta-qá-ma ||| I will wait for 5 days
šu-ma ha-ra-nam a-na Ha-tim lá ú-ta-šé-er ||| if he has not set the road to Hattum free
iš-tù A-šùr-ták-lá-ku É.GAL-lúm iṣ-bu-tù-ni ||| the palace seized Aššur-taklaku
A-šùr-ták-lá-ku wa-ší-ra mì-ma ar-nam ù ší-lá-tám lá ir-ší-a-ku-nu-tí ||| He wished no sin or evil upon you
a-wi-lam ša iš-tù Ta-wi-ni-a ṭup-pá-am ú-šé-bi-lá-ni ||| Bring me the man who sent the letter from Tawiniya
ru-ba-um Wa-áš-ha-na-i-um i-sí-ni-a-tí-ma e-li-a-nim ||| The king of Wašhaniya called upon us, saying: 'Come up here'
i-na dUTU-ši ru-ba-um wa-áš-ha-na-i-um i-na sí-kà-tí-im i-tù-ra-ni ||| The day the King of Wašhaniya returns from the sikkātum
áš-pu-ra-ku-nu-tí um-ma a-na-ku-ma AN.NA-ki ša bi-lá-tim ag-ra-ma a-na Ni-na-ša-a li-ší-ú-nim a-ša-me-ma a-li-ki a-na Wa-áš-ha-ni-a lá ú-šu-ru šu-ma Wa-ah-šu-ša-na-i-im ù Kà-ni-ší-im ša ma-mì-tám ub-lu-ni-ni ṭup-pí ik-ta-áš-dam i-na sí-ki-im dí-na-ma li-ší-ú-nim ||| I wrote to you, saying: 'Hire some porters (from Kaneš) to bring my tin to Nenašša'. I hear that they will not set travellers free to go to Wašhaniya. If my letter has reached you (concerning that) they have brought the Wahšušanean and the Kanišite an oath, then give (the tin) in a sikkum so that they can bring it.
šu-ma a-dí-ni i-Kà-ni-iš wa-áš-ba-tí a-na Wa-áš-ha-ni-a et-qá-ma a-dí ma-tum i-nu-hu lá té-ra-ba-am ||| If you are still in Kaneš, then travel to Wašhaniya, but do not enter until the Land settles down.
1 me-at TÚG.HI.A SIG5-tim 3 ni-nu a-na ru-ba-im Wa-áš-ha-na-i-im ha-bu-lá-ni 4 li-mì-im 6 me-at URUDU ú ší-im 10 MA.NA AN.NA šu-ut ha-bu-lá-ni-a-tí a-ha-ma ší-im 1 me-at TÚG.HI.A šu-ut-ma ha-bu-lá-ni-a-tí ||| The three of us owe 100 textiles of good quality to the king of Wašhaniya. He owes us 4600 (minas) of copper and the proceeds on 10 minas of tin. In addition, he personally owes us the price of 100 textiles
[a]-na ší-i[p-ri ša A-lim] ú kà-ri-[im Kà-ni-iš] [q]í-bi-ma um-ma kà-ru-[um] [W]a-ah-šu-ša-na-ma [r]u-ba-um ša Wa-áš-ha-⌈ni-a⌉ [iš]-pu-ra-am um-ma šu-ut-ma [ku-sí]-a-am ša a-bi4-a [aṣ-b]a-at ma-mì- ||| To the envoys of the City and the Kaneš Colony from the Wahšušana Colony. The king of Wašhaniya has written to us, saying: 'I have seized the throne of my father. Let me swear an oath'.
be-el a-lim ||| town prefect
i-na Ni-na-ša-a-a iš-tí ru-ba-im a-na-me-er-ma mì-ma-ša-ma ú-lá i-dí-nam um-ma šu-ut-ma iš-tù Ú-lá-ma tù-ra-am 1 TÚG a-na ší-mì-im mì-ma ú-lá il5-qé ||| I met with the king in Ninašša, but he did not give me anything. He said: 'Come back from Ulama (first)'. He did not buy a single textile.
ur-ki-a-ma iš-tù Ni-na-ša-a-a A-šur-DÙG e-tí-qám-ma 4 GÚ AN.NA ku-nu-ki ša A-lá-hi-im ù li-wi-sú-nu il5-qé-ma a-na Pu-ru-uš-ha-tim ú-bi-il5 ||| Thereupon, Aššur-ṭab travelled here from Ninašša, and he took the 4 talents of tin under the seal of Ali-ahum and their wrappings and brought (it) to Purušhaddum.
kà-ru-um Wa-ah-šu-ša-na ṣa-he-er ra-bi dí-nam i-dí-ma a-dí-i a-we-lim ša i-na Ni-na-ša-a a-na na-ri-im iṭ-ru-du ||| The plenary assembly of the Wahšušana Colony passed a verdict. In regard to the man, whom they sent to the river in Ninašša
a-šu-mì pí-ra-kà-ni ku-a-ú-tim ša Du-du i-dí-na-ni a-na Wa-ah-šu-ša-na a-na e-ra-bi-im a-zi-zi-ma ṭé-ri-tum i-ta-áš-kà-an-ma iš-tù ša-pá-at Zu-li-a na-ri-im ur-kà-tí-a a-tù-wa-ar a-na Ni-na-ša-a ú-ba-al-šu-nu ||| Concerning the pirikannukutānum textiles belonging to you that Dudu gave me: I stood ready to go into Wahšušana, but there was too much mud, so I will turn back from the bank of River Zuliya and bring them to Ninašša.
a-na kà-ri-im Kà-ni-iš qí-bi-ma um-ma ší-ip-ru-ku-nu ù kà-ru-um Wa-ah-šu-ša-na-ma ṭup-pè-e wa-bar-tum ša Ú-lá-ma ù Ša-lá-tù-ar ú-šé-bi4-lu-nim-ma ni-iš-ta-me-ma ni-ik-nu-uk-ma na-áš-ú-ni-ku-nu-tí i-ša-am-ší ṭup-pè-e ni-iš-ta-me-ú 2 ší-ip-ri ha-ra-an Ú-lá-ma-ma 2 ší-ip-ri ha-ra-an Ša-lá-tù-ar-ma a-na Pu-ru-uš-ha-dim a-na a-wa-tim za-ku-im ni-iš-ta-pár ||| To the Kaneš Colony from your envoys and the Wahšušana Colony. We have heard the tablets that the Stations of Ulama and Šalatuwar sent to us, we have sealed them, and now they are bringing them to you. The day we heard the tablets, we sent two messengers by the Ulama route and two messengers by the Šalatuwar route to Purušhaddum to clear the order.
a-na Ša-lá-tí-wa-ar ha-ra-na-tum lá na-ṭù a-[tù]-ar-ma a-na Ú-la-ma e-li ||| The roads to Šalatuwar are not feasible, so I will turn around and go up to Ulama.
iš-tù Dur4-hu-mì-it URUDU a-na Pu-ru-uš-ha-dim is-ri-id-ma 1 ANŠE-šu URUDU a-dí Wa-ah-šu-ša-na is-ri-⌈id-ma⌉ i-na ma-ṣa-ra-tim ša ha-ra-an Ú-la-ma ú-šé-ṣí-šu-nu ù a-tù-ra-am ||| He packed the copper (to go) from Durhumit to Purušhaddum, and he packed his own donkey to (go) as far as Wahšušana, and then I led them (the remaining donkeys) out with the help of the guard-posts on the Ulama road and I returned.
