a-na Tu-ni-ia ÌR-di-ia qí-bí-ma um-ma La-ba-ar-na LUGAL GAL-ma ÌR-di at-ta ú-ṣur-an-ni ù a-na-ku ÌR-di <lu>ú-ṣur-ka URUTi4-ku-na-an URU-lim ù at-ta ÌR-di ù KUR-at-ka KUR-ti lu-ú-ṣur-ka KASKAL-ti-nia pí-te-et ù it-ti LÚ URUHa-hi-ia-ú lu-ú i-la-at ŠE.BA-šu ki-ma UR.GI7 a-ku-ul-šu GUD.HI.A ša ta-la-qè lu-ú ku-ú U8.UDU.HI.A ša ta-la-qè-ma lu-ú ku-ú-ma a-na mu-hi-šu lu-ú 2? i-la-at a-na-ku iš-tu an-na-nu-um ù at-ta iš-tu a-nu-um-ma-nu AN.BAR-zi-lu-ú ù UR.MAH ša iš-tu URUNi-ih-ri-ia ú-te-ru eš-me i-na-an-na šu-bi-lam ù ha-ši-ih-ta-ka ma-la ha-aš-ha-tam šu-up-ra-am-ma lu-ša-bi-la-kum lu-ú KÙ.BABBAR lu-ú ANŠE.KUR.RA ù ÌR-di húp-ti ÌR-di É-ti lu-ú-ša-bi-la-ak-kum i-nu-ma i-na URUZa-al-pa-ar a-la-kam-ma mBu-ul-li ÌR-di ù ÌR-ka šu-up-ra-aš-šu-nu-ti šum-ma qa-ni?-iKUŠ i-ba-aš-ši-ma šu-bi-lam ù za-ap-pí ANŠE.KUR.RA lu-ú pé-ṣú-ti lu-ú ṣa-al-mu-ti šu-bi-<la>-aš-šu-nu-ti ù a-wa-ti ša-ra-ti ša i-dá-bu-ub la ta-ša-mi qa-ni ri-mi ú-ṣur ù ši-bá-aṭ UR.MAH ú-ṣur ši-bá-aṭ še-la-bi-i la ta-aṣ-ba-at ša ša-ra-ti i-te-né-pu-uš ki-ma URUZa-al-pa-ar-ma e-pu-šu ù ša-tum qa-tam-ma e-pu-uš i-mi-tum ù <<ù>> šu-mé-lum a-wa-ti la te-eš-te-né-mi a-wa-ti-ia ú-ṣur ||| Speak to Tuniya, my servant. Thus the Labarna, the Great King. You are my servant. Protect me, and I will protect you, my servant. Tikunan is my city and you are my servant, and your land is my land, and I will protect you. My campaign is ready, and the man of Hahhum has prepared his forces. Devour his provisions like a dog. The oxen you take will be yours. The sheep you take will also be yours. There will be two assaults against him: I from here, and you from there. Now send me the iron and the lion, which I heard that they have returned from Nihriya, and then, whatever you wish for, as much as you want, write to me and I will send it to you – silver, horses, prisoners and local slaves I will send. When I arrive at Zalpar, send my servant Bulli and your servant to me. If there are qani at hand, then send that to me. Also, have them bring white or black horsehairs to me. Also, do not listen to the lies he utters, but keep to the bull's horns, protect the tail of the lion, and do not hold on to the tail of the fox – the one who constantly produces lies. What I did to Zalpar, I will do to him. Do not ever listen to words on the right or left. Heed my words.
a-na ⌈be-lí⌉-ia qí-bí-ma um-ma Ia-si-im-su-mu-ú ÌR-ka-a-ma aš-šum e-te-eq mQa-qa-da-nim a-na Ha-aš-šiki a-na Ap-la-ha-an-da aq-bi ||| To my Lord from Yasim-sumu, your servant. I spoke to Aplahanda (king of Carchemish) in regard to Qaqqadanum's journey to Haššum
i-na pá-ni-tim-ma áš-pu-ra-kum um-ma a-na-ku-ma šu-ma ILLAT-at-kà i-sà-ri-dam ù a-ta qá-dí-ma ILLAT-tí-kà sí-ir-dam-ma lu-qú-tám ša DAM.GÀR ša ta-ra-dí-ú TÚG.HI.A SIG5-tim bi-ir-ma i-na Ma-na-ma ú-lá i-na Ú-na-ap-sé-e-sí ší-tí TÚG.HI.A ma-ṭí-ú-tim lu i-na ša DAM.GÀR i-ba-ší-ú lu ša bé-ú-lá-tí-kà ù-lu i-na ša bé-ú-lá-at ṣú-ha-re-e i-ba-ší-ú qá-dí-ma tap-pá-e-kà a-na É.GAL-lim le-ru-bu-nim ||| I wrote to you earlier, saying: 'If your caravan is being packed, then you too should pack together with your caravan, and choose textiles of good quality from the goods of the merchant that you are carrying, and in Mamma or in Unapsesi the rest of the less good textiles – both from what remains of the merchant's and from your own working capital and from the working capital of the servants – should enter the palace together with your partners.'
a-ni na-ab-ri-tum i-na Ur-šu i-ṣa-ba-at-ku-nu ki-ma ku-pá-um ma-du-ni a-na lu-qú-ut DAM.GÀR-ri-im ša ki-ma qá-qí-dí-a ú-lá áš-tap-ra-am ||| Now the winter has caught up with you in Uršu. Since there is a lot of snow, I have not sent anyone in whom I could trust to get the goods of the merchant
a-ṣé-er E-ni-ša-ri-im a-dí AN.NA-ki-kà Ú-ṣú-ur-ší-Ištar áš-ta-pá-ar iš-tù Za-al-pá i-tù-ru-nim-ma A-lá-ha-am a-ṭá-ra-dam ||| I have sent Uṣur-ša-Ištar to Enišarum concerning your tin. When they come back from Zalpa, I shall send Ali-ahum.
