1 me-at TÚG ku-ta-n[i?] 4 GÚ AN.NA ù i[t-ra]-/⌈sú⌉ 5 ANŠE.HI.A ša Šu-Be-lúm ù I-tur4-DINGIR i-n[a <gap> ] ù Tí-me-el-ki-a i[s-ni-qú-ni] a-na ta-ší-at AN.N[A-ki-a] ù TÚG.HI.A iš-tù Ha-hi-im a-dí Hu-ra-ma 2 ma-na 10 [GÍN] KÙ.BABBAR áš-qúl 1 ma-na KÙ.BABBAR a-na ší-ip-ri ša a-na Ha-[hi-im] a-ṣé-er lu-qú-tim áš-ta-pu-ru ||| 100 kutānukutānum textiles, 4 talents of tin and its extras (on) 5 donkeys, which Šu-Belum and Itur-ili checked in Timelkiya and in [GN], I paid 2 minas 10 shekels of silver for the transport of the tin and the textiles from Hahhum to Hurama. 1 mina of silver was spent on the messengers that I kept sending to Hahhum for the goods
2 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ù 2 GÍN AN.NA iš-tù Tí-me-el-ki-a ANŠE i-mì-hi-iṣ-ma áš-qúl 6 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ù 6 GÍN AN.NA iš-tù Hu-ra-ma a-dí Kà-ni-iš áš-qúl ||| I paid 2 shekels of silver and 2 shekels of tin from Timelkiya because a donkey suffered a stroke. I paid six shekels of silver and six shekels of tin from Hurama to Kaneš
šu-ma i-na Ku-bu-ur-[na-at] Ha-na-ak-na-ak ú-lá Dur4-hu-mì-it TÚG-tí SIG5 a-ší-mì-im e-ri-šu-ku-nu 1/2 MA.NA.TA KÙ.BABBAR a-na i-ta-aṭ-lim dí-na lá ||| If they demand good textiles from you for sale, be it Kuburnat, in Hanaknak, or in Durhumit, then you should sell the good textiles for cash on delivery for half a mina a piece. Do not set (them) free for sale on credit
2 GÚ AN.NA 4 TÚG.SIG5 3 TÚG ša qá-tim ù ANŠE ṣa-lá-ma-am ša Pí-lá-ah-Ištar iš-tù Ha-hi-im ù-šé-ra-da-ni šu-ma 8 GÍN.TA a-na KÙ.BABBAR AN.NA dí-na ù té-er-tak-nu li-li-kam ||| 2 talents of tin, 4 textiles of good quality and 3 textiles of ordinary quality and a black donkey that Pilah-Ištar will lead down from Hahhum: if there is (a price of) 8 shekels of tin per shekel of silver, then sell the tin and send your message to me here
šu-ma 8 GÍN.TA a-na KÙ.BABBAR lá-šu a-na KÙ.BABBAR lá ta-da-na AN.NA a-na e-ba-ar Ša-la-ah-šu-wa lá ú-šé-tù-qú ||| If there is not (a price of) 8 shekels of silver per (mina to be had), then do not sell it for silver. Do not let them send the tin via Šalahšuwa
ki-ma ša-lá-am AN.NA-ki e-ba-ar Tí-me-el-ki-a-ma AN.NA a-na Dur4-hu-mì-id lu-šé-tí-qú ||| For the safety of my tin, they should let the tin travel via Timelkiya to Durhumit
a-dí ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim ša taš-pu-ra-ni-ma um-ma a-ta-ma ki-ma ša-lá-am KÙ.BABBAR-pì-a 1 GÍN ù qá-qá-da-tí-ma ša-lá-mì-im ep-ša ha-ra-an sú-qí-num i-pá-té-ma a-ma-lá té-er-tí-kà né-pá-áš ||| In regard to the Narrow Track that you wrote to me about saying: 'For the safety of my money, you should do (your best) to save every shekel of silver and headšadduātum tax'. When the Narrow Track opens we will do as (instructed) in your message
a-na Puzur4-A-šùr DU10-ṣí-lá-A-šùr A-šur-ba-ni dIM-ba-ni ù I-ku-pá-ša qí-bi4-ma um-ma Bu-za-zu-ma ||| To Puzur-Aššur, Buzazu says as follows
AN.NA iš-tí URUDU-i-ni a-na ba-ru-im lá-šu ||| tin together with copper is a burden for him
AN.NA-ki ú TÚG.HI-tí-a ||| tin and textiles
AN.NA a-na Hu-ra-ma lu-ub-lu-ni-šu-ma ||| let the tin be brought to Hurama
ri-ik-sí 10 MA.NA.TA ù 15 MA.NA.TA ||| packets of 10-15 minas each
AN.NA lu ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim lu i-pá-zu-ur-tim ||| tin by the Narrow Track or by smuggling
i-na 2 me-at 3[8 TÚG.HI.A] ša šé-ep I-dí-dIM <ša> a-na Né-ša a-na É.GAL-lim e-ru-bu-ni ŠÀ.BA 21 TÚG SIG5 ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim a-na Du-ur-mì-it i-tal-ku ||| Out of the 238 textiles, transported by Iddin-Adad, that entered the palace in Neša, 21 good textiles have gone off to Durhumit by the Narrow Track.
[<gap> (<gap>) ha-r]a-an sú-qí-nim-ma [a-na Du-ur-hu]-mì-it [ú-là Tí-iš-m]u-ur-na a-li [<gap> (<gap> )] qá-bi4-a-ku-ni-tí-ni ||| on the Narrow Track, and either to Durhumit or to Tišmurna, wherever <gap> that I have promised to you.
a-na lu-qú-tim ša ha-[ra-an] sú-qí-nim li-bi4 pá-ri-id a-ma-kam [lu PN] lu ma-ma-an a-hi-ú-um iš-tí-šu-nu i-li-ik ša-il5-ma iš-tí pá-ni-im-ma a-li-ki-im té-er-ta-kà li-l[i-kam] ú a-na-ku a-na Dur4-hu-mì-it áš-ta-pá-ar ||| I am worried about the goods destined for the Narrow Track. Ask around whether somebody else has departed with them, and let your message come to me with the first ālikum, then I will myself write to Durhumit.
um-ma I-na-a-ma a-na A-šur-DÙG ú MAN-A-šur qí-bi-ma a-na-kam ru-ba-um ù ru-ba-tum a-na ha-ra-na-tim ša pá-zu-ur-tim iš-pu-ru-ma um-ma šu-nu-ma ša i-ma-tim TÚG.HI.A ù AN.NA na-áš-ú-ma ša ta-ma-ra-ni ṣa-áb-ta-ma AN.NA ú TÚG.HI.A a-tù-nu kà-i-lá-ma ra-ga-am i-a-tí ri-id-a ú a-na ša ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim iš-ta-áp-ru a-pu-tum AN.NA ù TÚG.HI.A lá tù-pá-za-ra ú a-na ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim mì-ma lá ša-kà-na a-pu-tum a-wa-tum da-na-at mì-ma e šé-bi4-lá-ma li-ba-ak-nu e im-ra-aṣ ṭup-pá-am ší-ta-me-šu-ma a-na A-šur-DÙG še-bi4-il5-šu ||| Thus (say) Ina'a to Aššur-ṭab and the king's wife: the king and the queen have sent word to the caravan (about) the Narrow Track, thus they say: (Regarding) what you are carrying - textiles and tin - (if) you have taken tin and textiles, they are under lock and seal, and he shall lead (them). And to the matter of the Narrow Track they have sent word: Do not send anything by the Narrow Track without authorization. This is the firm word: Do not send anything, lest you be sorry. Hear the letter carefully and send it to Aššur-ṭab.
ta-áš-pu-ra-am um-ma a-ta-ma ha-ra-ni a-na a-limki et-qá-ni-ma [a-w]a-at-ku-nu [da-n]a-a a-bu-ni [a-ta] ki-ma [a-w]a-tum a-ma-kam [d]a-na-ni-ma ṣa-ah-ru-um a-ri-ni-iš lá e-ra-ba-ni ù a-na-nu-um a-na-kam lu-qú-tum ša ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim i-ṣí-ib-tù-ni a-ší-a-tí da-ni-ša-ma a-na e-ra-bi4-im ni-ip-ta-lá-ah a-bu-ni a-ta a-wa-tum ša É.GAL-lim li-id-mi-qá-ma i-na SIG5-tim a-ri-ni-iš lu!? n[é-ru-ub] ||| You wrote, saying: 'I am going to the City. Travel over – your (pl.) messages are strict'. Our dear father, given that the orders are strict there, that a junior cannot enter <gap> , and that also goods, which were on the Narrow Track here, have been seized here, for that reason we are very anxious about entering (the track). Our dear father, when the orders of the palace soften, and the <gap> , then we will e[nter].
a-wa-at kà-ri-im da-na a-dì-i pá-zu-ur-ti-kà ša ta-áš-pu-ra-ni lá na-ṭù-ma a-dì-i pá-zu-ur-ti-kà lá ni-ša-pá-ra-kum ||| Since the orders of the Colony are strict, your (idea of) smuggling that you wrote to us about is not possible. Therefore we will not write about your smuggling
um-ma kà-ru-um Kà-ni-iš-ma a-na ša-qí-il5 da-tim Ku-li-a ší-ip-ri-ni wa-bar-tim ša Ku-bur-na-at Ha-na-ak-na-ak ú Tí-iš-mur-na TUR GAL <gap> ni-ša-me-ma 30 ANŠE Tù-i-mu-um DUMU A-[šùr a]-na ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim ú-š[é-ri-b]a-am lá Tù-i-mu-um ma-ma-[an] ha-ra-an sú-qí-nim e-ma-r[e] sé-er-dam ú-šé-ri-ba-ni-ma a-ma-kam uš-té-bu-lu-ni lu wa-ší-ib kà-ri-im ú-šé-li-a-am GÍR ša A-šur šé-ṣí-a-ma a-hu-um pá- ||| Thus says the Kaneš Colony to the dātum-payers, Kuliya our messenger, and the plenary assemblies of the Stations in Kuburnat, Hanaknak and Tišmurna <gap> We hear that Tu'imum, an Assyrian, has brought in 30 donkeys by way of the Narrow Track. Not only Tu'imum, but anybody, who has brought in loaded donkeys by way of the Narrow Track in order to do business here, or if an inhabitant of a Colony has made (goods) come up there, produce the dagger of (divine) Assur and people shall not spare each other.
i-n[u-m]ì a-na Tí-me-el-ki-a a-ṣé-er lu-qú-tim e-tí-qú 1/3 MA.NA KÙ.BABBAR a-sà-he-er-tim 10 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR a-É ub-ri 5 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR É wa-á[b-r]i i-na Ša-lá-ah-šu-a 5 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR É u[b-ri] i-Hu-ra-ma 6 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR a-na kà-ší-im i-H[u-r]a-ma 1/2 GÍN KÙ.BABBAR ú-qá-li-lá-ni ||| When I travelled to Timelkiya to meet up with the goods: a third mina of silver for sundries. Ten shekels of silver for inns: Five shekels of silver for inns in Šalahšuwa (and) five shekels of silver for inns in Hurama. 6 shekels of silver for the official in Hurama – he fooled me out of half a shekel of silver.
1/3 MA.NA 2 [GÍN] KÙ.GI ša Š[a!-lá-ah-šu-a] SIG5 DIRIG Bu-[<gap>] a-na I-ku-pì-[A-šur?] i-ša-qal DU[B!-pá-am ša] 1/3 MA.NA KÙ.GI ša ku-nu-ki-[šu] ú-ša-ar-šu-[um] šu-ma KÙ.GI ša Ša-lá-ah-šu-a lá uš-té-bi4-lam 3 MA.NA 6 GÍN K[Ù.BABBAR] i-ša-qal-šu-um ||| 1/3 mina and 2 shekels of gold of extra good quality of Š[alahšuwa] will weigh out to Ikuppi-[Aššur?]. He (Ikuppi-[Aššur?]) will (then) set the (debt) tablet of 1/3 mina of gold with his seal free to him. If he does not send him the gold from Šalahšuwa, he must pay him 3 minas and 6 shekels of s[ilver] (instead).
11 LÁ 1 TÚG.HI.A Ša-lá-ah-šu-a-i-ú ub-lu-nim ŠÀ.BA 6 TÚG.HI.A ša Kur-ub-Ištar iš-té-en ku-nu-ku-šu lá-šu 6 GÍN KÙ a-na Ša-lá-ah-šu-a-i-e a-dí-in ||| Out of the eleven minus one textile that the Šalahšuwean brought to me, six belong to Kurub-Ištar. One had no seal. I have paid the Šalahšuweans six shekels of silver.
1/2 ma-na URUDU ú sà-he-er-tám i-Hi-ra-áš-ta ||| 30 shekels of copper and sundries in Hirašta
1/3 ma-na 10 GÍN URUDU i-na Bu-ul-bu-ul-hi-im ||| 30 shekels of copper in Bulbulhum
mì-ma a-nim i-Ma-a-ma áš-qúl ||| all of this I paid in Mamma
a-na-kam dí-iš-pu-um lá-šu a-na Ur-šu-ú ni-ša-pá-ar-ma dí-iš-pá-am ú-šé-lu-nim i-na Ú-ni-ip-sí-im a-šu-mì ṣú-ùh-ri-im u4-ma-kál ni-is-hu-ur-ma DUMU Ha-am-ha-am-t[im] i-pá-ni-ni a-na Ma-a-ma i-tí-li-ma lá ni-ik-šu-sú ||| There is no honey here, and so we will write to Uršu so that they can bring some honey up here. We have been delayed due to the children in Unipsum, and (since) the son of Hamhamtum has gone up to Mamma ahead of us, we have not caught up with him
KÙ.BABBAR šu-a-tí a-ru-ba-im Ma-ma-im ú-šé-bi-lu-šu ||| [silver referenced in relation to Mamma]
a-lu-a-ri-im ki-ra-nim ṭá-bi-im ||| alluāru-container of sweet wine
2 ANŠE ṣa-lá-mu ||| 2 donkeys
4 ma-na LÁ 15 GÍN 9 ma-na.TA ta-dí-in ||| 4 minas less 15 shekels at 9 minas each
3 ma-na 15 GÍN na-áš-ú-ni-kum ||| 3 minas 15 shekels, they bring to you
15 GÚ 24 2/3 ma-na URUDU ma-sí-um ||| 15 talents 24 2/3 minas of washed copper
1 GÚ-tum 1 ma-na.TA i-na ša-bu-ri-im im-ṭí ||| One mina per talent was missing during the breaking up
2 1/2 ma-na URUDU SIG5 i-li-bi4 URUDU-i-kà ni-dí a-na ta-ší-a-at URUDU ša Áb-ša-lim ù Dan-A-šùr ||| We deposited 2 ½ minas of good copper out of your copper and gave it to Ab-šalim for the carriage of Ab-šalim's and Dan-Aššur's copper
