a-še-er li-bi4 la-am-nu KU.BABBAR am-si-ma i-na 5 ma-na 3 1/3 ma-na e-li-a-am a-na-kam-ma ||| Not only am I furious, but I refined the silver and out of 5 minas only 3 1/3 minas came up
1 l/2 GIN AN.NA i-na Ta-pa-kG-as a-ka-si-im a-di-in ||| I paid 1 1/2 shekels of tin to the official in Tapaggas
is-tu A-sur-tak-ta-ku E.GAL-lum i-y-bu-tu-ni ITU.2.KAM i-li-ik-ma ka-ru-um a-na E.GAL-lim e-li-ma um-ma ka-ru-um-ma A-sur-tak-la-ku wa-si-ra mi-ma ar-nam it si-la-ttim la ir-si-a-ku-nu-ti qa-di-ni-ma i-na a-li-ku-nu E be-ram i-su u a-na e-ri-is-ti-ku-nu qa-di-ni-ma i-za-az ||| Two months passed since the palace seized Assur-taklaku and then the Colony went up to the palace and said: 'Free Assur-taklaku. He wished no sin or evil upon you. He has a house among us in your city, and with us, he stands at your service'.
um-ma ru-ba-um it ru-ba-tum-ma a-wi-lam sa is-tu Ta-wi-ni-a tup-pa-am u-se-bi-la-ni-ma e-ri-is-tam a-na be-el nu-ku-ur-ti-ni i-za-bi-lu-ma qa-qa-ad-ni i-se-e-u-ni ni-a-nim-ma a-hu-ku-nu lu-se-er ||| The king and the queen replied: 'Bring me the man who sent the letter from Tawiniya, who carried out the wishes of our enemy, and who seeks our head, then I shall set your brother free'.
um-ma ka-ru-um-ma li-zi-iz i-na GIR sa A-sur li-it-ma si-ma-am la is-u-mu-ma a-na Ta-wi-ni-a ta u-se-bi-lu a-na e-ri-is-ti Ta-wi-ni-a-i-im la i-za-zu zi-ta ki-ma me-ra a-li-ku-nu a-na i-dim li-li-ik u-la ne-nu a-pu-hi-su GIR sa A-sur lu ni-it-ma ||| Then the Colony said: 'Let him step forward and swear upon the dagger of Assur that he has neither bought nor sent any goods to Tawiniya, (and that) he will not carry out the wishes of the Tawiniyan. Alternatively, he can go to the River as (if he were) a citizen of your city, or we can swear upon the dagger of Assur in his stead'.
um-ma ru-ba-um u ru-ba-tum-ma sa tup-pa-am qa-at-ni u-ka-lzi ku-nu-ti u-ta-ma-ku-nu a-wi-lam ru-a-nim su-ma lQ ta-ra-di-a-ni-su I ma-na a-mu-tam u-la I 0 ma-na KU.GI di-na-nim-ma a-hu-ku-nu-lu-se-er su-ma la-ta-da-na la ta-tu-ra-ma su-um-su la ta-za-ka-ra a-hu-ku-nu me-et ||| The king and queen replied: 'Since our hand holds the letter it is yourselves whom I will make swear your oath. Bring us that man. If you do not lead him here then give us one mina of amiitum or ten minas of gold so I may release your brother. If you do not pay up, then do not return and do not mention his name again. Your brother will be dead'.
urn-rna ru-b[a-um] sa Tu-uh-pi-a-ma a-na Ptur4 1-DINGIR qi-bi-ma ||| To Itur-ili from Isma-Assur
a-na er-bi-im i-si-am ||| for a gift
i-na Ni-na-sa-a 15 ma-na URUDU ag-mu-ur 10 ma-na [a]-na ag-ri-im [sa] is-ti-a is-hu-ru [as-q ]ul i-na Wa-a.l:-ha-ni-a a-di-su-um 5 ma-na URUDU i/5-qe i.Hu Ni-na-sa-a u-~i-ma i-na At-hu-ru-us-na 5 ma-na URUDU i-~e-ri-a i/5-qe-u ||| In Ninassa 15 minas of copper I completed. 10 minas for the hireling who was delayed with me I paid. In Washaniya he received (it). 5 minas of copper he took. He left Ninassa, and in Athurusna 5 minas of copper on my account he took.
a -§ar ha-ra-an Ma-li-ta-ma a-[n ]a [Wa ]-ah-su-sa-na i-ta-a[p-te-u] ||| at the place where the Malitta road to Wahsusana opens
is-tit Dur4-hu-mi-it URUDU a-na Pu-ru-us-ha-dim is-ri-id-ma ANSE-su URUDU a-di Wa-ah-su-sa-na is-ri-id-ma i-na ma-sa-ra-tim saha-ra-an U-la-ma u-se-su-nu it a-tit-ra-am ||| He packed the copper (to go) from Durhumit to Purushaddum, and he packed his own donkey to (go) as far as Wahsusana, and then I led them (the remaining donkeys) out with the help of the guard posts on the Ulama road and I returned.
4 GiN.TA KU.BABBAR a-di U-ul-ma-a ni-a-ti da-tum ik-su-ud 5 GiN KU.BABBAR a-na sa-da-dim as-qul 10 GiN KU.BABBAR a-na KU-ri-im as-qul GiN a-di U-ul-ma [ik]-su-ud-ni-a-ti 1 1/2 GIN.TA KU.BABBAR is-tit Du-ur-hu-mi-it ik-su-ud-ni-a-ti ||| Four shekels per (donkey) came on as fees until Ulama. I paid 5 shekels of silver for the (cart) transport. I paid 10 shekels of silver to the Colony. The (expenses) for us until Ulama amounted to 1 shekel. The (expenses) for each of us from Durhumit amounted to one and half a shekel.
si-kG-tum ru-qa-ma KU.BABBAR-pu sa-du-u su-ma ta-da-num te-er-ta-ka li-li-kam-ma KU.BABBAR 5 ma-na it 6 ma-na le-pu-us-ma lu-se-bi-la-kum [ ]-na u-sa-lam-ma [1 ma]-na 17 GiN.TA [ ] U-la-ma URUDU it [ ] X i-na [Sa-la-t]u-ar URUDU-um [da-mu]-qu-um 1 ma-na 13 GiN.TA i-za-az su-ma a-na Sa-la-tu-ar u 10 GU a-na U-la-ma a-sa-ri-id e-ma-ri se-ri-a-ma r e 1-[ ma ]-ri la a-sa-qal [is-ti] a-li-ki-im pa-ni-e-ma [te-er-t]a-ka li-li-kam [it e-m ]a-ri et-qam ||| The sikkatum has withdrawn but the silver is delayed. If there is trade, write to me and I will make 5-6 minas of silver and send it to you[ <gap> ] settles down, and[ <gap> the price] of copper in Ulama is 17 shekels per mina, and in Salatuwar good copper is sold at a rate of 13 shekels per mina. If I am to pack 10 talents of copper to Salatuwar or Ulama, then send me some donkeys so that I will not have to buy donkeys. Let your message reach me with the first traveller and make donkeys travel here.
