ki-ma a-wa-at na-ru-a-im DUMU A-sur su-um-su KU.GI a-na a-ki-di-im a-mu-ri-im u su-bi-ri-im ma-ma-an Ia i-da-an sa i-du-nu u-lci i-ba-la-at ||| In accordance with the words of the stele, a citizen of Assur may not pay any gold to an Akkadian, an Amorite, or a Subarean. The one who does pay (in gold) will not live
ina-nu-mi lu-qu-tum a-ni-tum u-ša-a-ni u4-mu-u ka-šu A-bu-ša-lim iš-ti ma-ma-an ina a-hi-ni ša u-ša-ld-ma-šu-ni pi-iq-da-šu-ma lu-ša-am šu-ma u4-mu-u e-mu-u la u-ša-a-am ||| If the days are cold when this merchandise leaves (Assur), you must entrust Abu-salim in the care whichever of our brothers that can bring him safely here, and then let him depart with (him). But if the days are hot he must not depart.
li-ba-ka ša i-la-mi-in la li-bi4 DINGIR-ma pi-ri-tum i-li-bi ma-tim i-si-ki-ma a-si-a-ti I ITU u 2 ITU ak-ta-ta a-di ma-tum is-li-mu it ši-ti KU.BABBAR-pi-ku-nu is-ti a-li-ki wa-ar-ki-u-tim u-še-ba-la-kum ||| Alas, fear is placed in the heart of the land, and for that reason I have been held back for a couple of months. As soon as the land settles down, I will send the rest of your money with the first travellers (leaving).
ina su-ku-ur-tim a-na ni-si-a ba-lu-[im I 1/2 ma-na KU.BABBAR E nu-a-e a-si-ma ||| To keep my people alive during the blockade, I took out a loan of 1 1/2 shekels of silver from the house of a native Anatolian.
si-ti AN.NA-ka ki-ma si-ka-tu-ni a-di-ni na-di i-na tu-wa-ar si-ka-tim AN.NA-ka a-da-ma a-ta-be-a-ma a-ta-la-kam si-ka-tum da-na a-di tu-wa-ar ka-ni-si-im ra-ma-ka sa-~e-er Ia te-ra-ba-am ||| Since there is sikkatum, the rest of the tin remains stored. When the sikkatum returns I will sell you your tin, and then I will get up and leave. The sikkatum is fierce. Take care of yourself, and do not enter until the return of the Kanes site (king).
